window.DEEPDIVES = [
  /* ===================================================== CACHING ==== */
  { id: "dd-cache", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "⚡", level: "Beginner → Advanced", title: "Caching", tagline: "Trade a little freshness for huge speed by keeping hot data close.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why (start here)", p: ["A cache is a small, fast store placed in front of a slower, bigger store. You keep copies of frequently used data so most reads finish in microseconds instead of milliseconds, and your expensive backend (database, disk, network service) is shielded from repeated identical work.","The whole field rests on one hardware truth: each storage layer is roughly 100x slower than the one above it. RAM is ~100x faster than SSD; a local call is ~100x faster than a cross-region network hop. So if a piece of data is read far more often than it changes, copying it to a faster layer is the single biggest, cheapest latency win you will ever make.","Two numbers decide everything: hit rate (fraction of reads served by the cache) and the cost of a miss. A 95% hit rate means 19 of 20 reads are instant and your DB only sees 1; pushing it to 99% cuts DB load five-fold again. That is why teams obsess over hit rate."], bullets: ["L1 ~1ns · RAM ~100ns · SSD ~100µs · disk ~10ms · cross-region ~50–150ms.", "Effective latency = hit_rate×fast + miss_rate×slow. 95% hits over a 5ms DB → ~0.35ms average.", "Goal: maximize hit rate, minimize staleness, survive cache failure."] },
    { h: "A tiny bit of history", p: ["Caching began in 1960s CPUs: a few KB of SRAM sat between the processor and slow core memory because the CPU kept stalling waiting for data. The mantra became 'exploit locality' — temporal (you reuse the same thing soon) and spatial (you use neighbors next).","The web copied it wholesale: browser caches, then proxy caches like Squid (1990s), then memcached (2003, built at LiveJournal to take load off MySQL), then Redis (2009) which added data structures and persistence. The idea never changed — a fast tier fronting a slow tier — only the layer moved."] },
    { h: "Where caches live (the chain)", p: ["A real system has many caches stacked from the user inward. A request is ideally answered as early as possible:"], bullets: ["Browser cache — HTTP Cache-Control/ETag; zero network.","CDN / edge — static assets and cacheable GETs near the user.","Reverse-proxy cache — Varnish/Nginx in front of the app.","Application in-process cache — a HashMap in the service; fastest, but per-instance and not shared.","Distributed cache — Redis/Memcached cluster; shared across all servers, the workhorse.","Database buffer pool — the DB caches hot pages in RAM."], note: "Layered caching means even a CDN miss can hit Redis, and a Redis miss hits the DB buffer pool before disk." },
    { h: "Read pattern: cache-aside", p: ["The default. The application owns the logic: check cache, on miss load from DB and populate. It is resilient (cache down ≠ outage, just slower) and only caches data actually requested.","Downsides: the first request for any key is always a miss, and the app must remember to invalidate on writes."], code: `Object get(String k){\n  Object v = cache.get(k);\n  if (v == null) {              // miss\n    v = db.load(k);\n    cache.set(k, v, TTL);        // populate for next time\n  }\n  return v;\n}` },
    { h: "Read pattern: read-through & refresh-ahead", p: ["Read-through: the cache library itself loads from the DB on a miss, so app code just calls cache.get — cleaner, but the cache must support a loader. Refresh-ahead proactively reloads hot keys shortly before they expire so popular data never misses. Both reduce miss latency at the cost of more machinery."] },
    { h: "Write patterns (3 ways)", p: ["How writes keep cache and DB in sync:"], bullets: ["Write-through: write cache + DB together. Cache always fresh; writes pay both costs.","Write-back (write-behind): write cache now, flush to DB asynchronously. Fastest, absorbs bursts, but a crash loses unflushed data.","Write-around: write DB only, let cache fill on read. Avoids caching write-once data, but recent writes miss."] , code: `// write-through\nvoid put(String k,Object v){ db.save(k,v); cache.set(k,v,TTL); }` },
    { h: "Eviction policies (the core)", p: ["Memory is finite, so when full the cache must drop something. The policy is the heart of a cache. LRU (least-recently-used) is the default: evict whatever was untouched longest, implemented as a hashmap + doubly linked list for O(1) get/put. LFU favors items used most often; FIFO is simplest; TTL expires by age; ARC adapts between recency and frequency.","Pick by workload: LRU for general hot/cold, LFU for stable popularity, TTL when freshness matters most."], code: `class LRU {                       // O(1) via map + DLL\n  Map<K,Node> map; Node head, tail;\n  V get(K k){ move(k, head); return map.get(k).v; }\n  void put(K k,V v){ if(size>cap) evict(tail.prev); insert(head,k,v); }\n}` },
    { h: "Invalidation — the hardest problem", p: ["'There are only two hard things in CS: cache invalidation and naming things.' Stale data is the price of speed. Strategies: a short TTL (let it expire), delete-on-write (drop the key when the source changes), or versioned keys (user:42:v8) so a new version is just a new key — no purge needed.","Always decide per data type how stale is acceptable: a price needs seconds, a profile photo can be hours. There is no universal answer, only a tradeoff you choose."] },
    { h: "Distributed caching & scale", p: ["One Redis node is capped by RAM and CPU, so you cluster it. Keys are spread with consistent hashing so adding/removing a node moves only ~1/N keys. Replicas serve reads and provide failover. The working set should fit in memory; size it from real key sizes × hot-key count, not the whole dataset."], bullets: ["Shard by key (consistent hashing).","Replicate hot keys / read replicas.","Local L1 cache in front of Redis L2 for ultra-hot keys."] },
    { h: "Failure modes (say these in interviews)", bullets: ["Thundering herd: a hot key expires, thousands hit the DB at once → single-flight lock (one loader) or staggered/jittered TTLs.","Cache stampede on cold start → warm the cache before traffic.","Penetration: queries for keys that never exist bypass cache → cache negatives or front with a Bloom filter.","Hot key: one key overwhelms a node → replicate it or add a local cache.","Avalanche: many keys expire together → randomize TTLs."] },
    { h: "Redis vs Memcached", bullets: ["Redis: rich types (lists, sets, sorted sets, streams), persistence, replication, pub/sub, Lua, locks — the Swiss-army knife.","Memcached: strings only, multithreaded, dead-simple, great pure cache.","Pick Redis unless you truly only need a plain LRU map."] },
    { h: "When NOT to cache", bullets: ["Write-heavy data (cache churns), strong-consistency needs (balances), read-once data, datasets the DB already serves in <1ms."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Keep cache consistent? cache-aside + delete-on-write + short TTL; accept eventual consistency.","p99 spikes on expiry? thundering herd → single-flight + jittered TTL.","Cache down — outage? cache-aside degrades to slow, not down.","Sizing? working-set × item size, with headroom for eviction."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================================== LOAD BALANCING ==== */
  { id: "dd-lb", cat: "Networking & Delivery", icon: "⚖️", level: "Beginner → Advanced", title: "Load Balancing", tagline: "One front door spreading traffic across many interchangeable servers.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["One server has finite CPU, memory, and open sockets — a few thousand to a few tens of thousands of concurrent connections. To serve more users and survive a crash you run many identical servers. But clients need a single stable address, and traffic must never go to a dead or overloaded node. A load balancer is that single front door: it spreads requests across healthy backends and quietly removes broken ones.","This one component is what makes horizontal scaling and high availability possible. Without it, adding servers does nothing because nobody knows about them, and one failure takes you down."], bullets: ["Distributes load · removes failures · enables zero-downtime deploys.","Pairs with stateless services so any node can serve any request."] },
    { h: "Origin", p: ["In the late 1990s sites outgrew a single box and hardware appliances (F5 BIG-IP, Cisco) appeared. Software LBs — HAProxy (2001), Nginx (2004), later Envoy — made it commodity, and cloud LBs (AWS ELB/ALB/NLB) made it a checkbox. The pattern is unchanged: a reverse proxy specialized for distribution and health."] },
    { h: "L4 vs L7", p: ["A Layer-4 LB routes on TCP/UDP: it forwards packets blindly, extremely fast, with no idea what's inside. A Layer-7 LB speaks HTTP: it can read path, host, cookies, and method, so it can route /api to one pool and /img to another, terminate TLS, retry, and rewrite. L7 is smarter but adds a little latency."], bullets: ["L4 (NLB): millions of connections, lowest latency.","L7 (ALB): content routing, TLS, auth, retries."] },
    { h: "Algorithms", p: ["How it picks a backend matters. Round-robin rotates evenly; weighted gives bigger boxes more; least-connections sends to the least busy (best when request times vary); IP/key hashing pins a client for affinity; power-of-two-choices picks two at random and takes the lighter — cheap and near-optimal."], code: `int next(){ int t=0,b=0;\n  for(int i=0;i<w.length;i++){ cur[i]+=w[i]; t+=w[i]; if(cur[i]>cur[b]) b=i; }\n  cur[b]-=t; return b; }   // smooth weighted round-robin` },
    { h: "Health checks (self-healing)", p: ["The LB pings each backend (e.g. GET /health) every few seconds. Failing nodes are ejected from rotation; recovered ones rejoin. Separate liveness (process broken → restart) from readiness (warming up → don't send traffic yet). Tune thresholds: too aggressive flaps, too lax routes to dead nodes."] },
    { h: "Global + regional", p: ["Big systems use two tiers. A global LB (DNS/Anycast/latency) sends a user to the nearest healthy region; a regional LB picks a node within it. Together they give low latency and survive a whole region failing."] },
    { h: "Stickiness", p: ["Sticky sessions pin a user to one node via cookie or IP hash, needed when state lives in memory. But it ruins even balance and breaks on failover. Prefer stateless services with state in Redis/DB, so the LB can send anyone anywhere."] },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["LB is a SPOF — run redundant LBs (Anycast/DNS).","Flapping health checks; reconnect storms on failover.","Least-connections skew with long-lived connections.","TLS termination CPU cost."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["ALB vs NLB: L7 routing vs L4 raw speed.","Scale the LB itself: Anycast across many.","Avoid dead nodes: health checks + ejection.","Stateful app: external session store over stickiness."] },
  ]},
  /* =========================================== CONSISTENT HASHING === */
  { id: "dd-chash", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "🧭", level: "Intermediate", title: "Consistent Hashing", tagline: "Add/remove nodes moving only ~1/N of data.", chapters: [
    { h: "Problem", p: ["The naive way to spread keys is hash(key) % N. It's even, but the moment N changes — a cache node dies, you add a shard — almost every key maps somewhere new. For a cache that means a near-total cold start; for a database that means moving nearly all the data. Consistent hashing changes only ~1/N keys when membership changes."] },
    { h: "Origin", p: ["Invented by Karger et al. at MIT (1997) for web caching, then popularized by Amazon's Dynamo paper (2007). Today it underpins DynamoDB, Cassandra, Riak, and most CDN routing."] },
    { h: "How it works", p: ["Map both nodes and keys onto a circular hash space (0..2^32). A key belongs to the first node found clockwise. Remove a node and only its keys slide to the next node; add one and it only steals a slice from its neighbor — everyone else is untouched."], code: `String get(String k){ var e = ring.ceilingEntry(hash(k)); return (e==null ? ring.firstEntry() : e).getValue(); }` },
    { h: "Virtual nodes", p: ["With few nodes the ring is lumpy and load skews. Give each server many points on the ring (vnodes); now load averages out and you can weight a bigger server with more vnodes. Rebalancing also gets smoother since one node's keys spread across many neighbors."] },
    { h: "Replication on the ring", p: ["Store each key on the next K nodes clockwise. If the primary dies, the next holds a copy. Combined with quorum reads/writes this gives availability + tunable consistency."] },
    { h: "Used in", bullets: ["Distributed caches, DynamoDB/Cassandra partitioning, CDN routing, sharded queues."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["Skew without enough vnodes; O(log V) lookup; range queries scatter; rebalancing must move replicas too."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Why vnodes? even spread + weighting + smooth rebalance.","Replication? next K clockwise.","hash%N problem? mass remap on resize."] },
  ]},
  /* ================================================== SHARDING ===== */
  { id: "dd-shard", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🧩", level: "Intermediate → Advanced", title: "Sharding", tagline: "Split data across machines to scale writes and storage.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Replication scales reads, never writes or dataset size. When a single primary can no longer hold the data or absorb the write rate, you split the data so each shard owns a slice and lives on its own machine — total capacity grows roughly linearly with nodes.","Sharding is the answer to 'one database is no longer enough', and simultaneously the source of most distributed-data pain: joins, transactions, and rebalancing all get harder. Delay it as long as replicas + caching suffice."] },
    { h: "Strategies", p: ["How you choose a shard decides everything. Hash sharding spreads evenly but kills range scans and is painful to resize. Range sharding keeps order (great for time ranges) but risks hotspots on recent data. Geo keeps data near users; directory uses a lookup table for flexibility at the cost of a hop."], code: `int shard(String key, int n){ return Math.floorMod(key.hashCode(), n); } // hash` },
    { h: "Routing", p: ["A router or coordinator maps key → shard and forwards each query; sometimes the client library holds the map. Adding shards should use consistent hashing so only ~1/N keys move instead of reshuffling everything."] },
    { h: "Cross-shard pain", p: ["A query touching many shards becomes scatter-gather: fan out, wait for the slowest, merge. Joins across shards don't exist — you denormalize. Transactions across shards need a saga or 2PC. Pagination and aggregates get tricky. Design so the common query hits one shard."], bullets: ["No cross-shard joins → denormalize.","No cross-shard ACID → saga.","Fan-out reads bound by slowest shard."] },
    { h: "Choosing the shard key", p: ["The key must have high cardinality, even access, and match the dominant query. user_id is the classic choice. Avoid low-cardinality keys (few buckets), sequential keys (all writes hit one shard), and celebrity keys (one user dominates). Salt or split hot keys."] },
    { h: "Rebalancing", p: ["As data grows you add shards. With plain hash%N you'd remap everything; with consistent hashing + virtual nodes only a slice moves. Move data in background, keep both old/new serving during cutover."] },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["Auto-increment/counter hotspot.","Cross-shard pagination + sort.","Hot shard from skewed key.","Resharding downtime."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Shard vs partition: same, shard=across machines.","Rebalance: consistent hashing + vnodes.","Cross-shard txn: saga.","Pick key: high cardinality, even, query-aligned."] },
  ]},
  /* ================================================ REPLICATION ==== */
  { id: "dd-repl", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "📑", level: "Intermediate", title: "Replication", tagline: "Copies for availability, read-scale, and durability.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["A single copy of data is two problems at once: if that node dies you lose everything, and all reads pile onto one machine. Replication keeps multiple synchronized copies so reads scale across replicas, a failure loses nothing, and you can fail over. It's how databases get high availability and read throughput before you ever reach for sharding."] },
    { h: "Topologies", p: ["Leader-follower: all writes go to one leader which streams its change-log to followers that serve reads — simple, the default. Multi-leader: write to several leaders (multi-region) with conflict resolution. Leaderless (Dynamo/Cassandra): write to any, read from a quorum, repair in background."], bullets: ["Leader-follower: easy, single writer.","Multi-leader: write locally, resolve conflicts.","Leaderless: R+W>N quorum."] },
    { h: "Sync vs async", p: ["Synchronous replication waits for a replica to ack before confirming the write — safe but slower and stalls if a replica is down. Asynchronous confirms immediately and streams later — fast, but a leader crash can lose the last few writes. Semi-sync (ack from one replica) is the common middle ground."] },
    { h: "Replica lag", p: ["Async replicas trail the leader by milliseconds to seconds. A user who just wrote may read a replica and not see their change. Fixes: read-your-writes (send their reads to the leader briefly), monotonic reads (pin to one replica), or wait for the replica to reach the write's log position (LSN)."], code: `Conn pick(boolean justWrote){ return justWrote ? leader() : replica(); }` },
    { h: "Failover & split-brain", p: ["On leader death a follower is promoted. Risks: lost un-replicated async writes, and split-brain if two nodes both think they're leader. Quorum + fencing tokens prevent two leaders. Failover must be rehearsed or it's just hope."] },
    { h: "Quorum math", p: ["With N replicas, requiring W write-acks and R read-acks: if R+W>N every read overlaps the latest write, so you read fresh. Lower R/W for speed and availability; raise for consistency — a tunable slider."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Stale read fix: sticky-to-leader / monotonic reads.","Quorum: R+W>N.","Sync vs async: safety vs latency.","Split-brain: quorum + fencing."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================================== CONSISTENCY ====== */
  { id: "dd-consistency", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "⚖️", level: "Advanced", title: "CAP, PACELC & Consistency", tagline: "The theory interviewers love — said precisely.", chapters: [
    { h: "CAP theorem", p: ["Three properties: Consistency (every read sees the latest write), Availability (every request gets a response), Partition tolerance (works despite dropped network messages). Networks WILL partition, so P is mandatory — the real choice is between C and A during a partition. CP systems reject some requests to stay correct (Zookeeper, HBase); AP systems serve possibly-stale data to stay up (Cassandra, Dynamo).","The myth is 'pick 2 of 3'. Truth: no partition → you get both C and A; only during a partition must you choose."] },
    { h: "PACELC", p: ["CAP ignores the normal case. PACELC: if Partition then A-or-C; Else (normal operation) Latency-or-Consistency. Most real stores trade a little consistency for lower latency even with no partition — that's why eventual consistency is everywhere."] },
    { h: "Consistency spectrum", p: ["Not binary. From strongest to weakest:"], bullets: ["Linearizable: looks like one copy, instant global order — strongest, costly.","Sequential/strong: latest write visible.","Causal: cause precedes effect; concurrent ops may differ.","Read-your-writes: you see your own updates.","Monotonic reads: never go backwards.","Eventual: converges someday; reads may be stale."] },
    { h: "ACID vs BASE", bullets: ["ACID: Atomic, Consistent, Isolated, Durable — correctness, single-node/SQL.","BASE: Basically Available, Soft state, Eventual — scale/availability, NoSQL.","They're ends of a spectrum, not a binary."] },
    { h: "Isolation levels", p: ["Within a DB, isolation controls what concurrent txns see. Read-committed avoids dirty reads; repeatable-read avoids non-repeatable reads; serializable avoids phantoms (fully isolated, slowest). Anomalies to name: dirty read, non-repeatable read, phantom, write skew."] },
    { h: "Quorum tuning", p: ["In leaderless stores you tune R and W out of N replicas. R+W>N guarantees overlap (strong-ish reads); lower them for speed/availability. This is the consistency slider in your hands."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Chat: AP, order via sequence numbers.","Bank balance: strong/ACID.","Feed: eventual is fine.","CAP only bites during partitions."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================================= MESSAGE QUEUE ===== */
  { id: "dd-mq", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "📨", level: "Beginner → Advanced", title: "Message Queues & Kafka", tagline: "Decouple producers/consumers, absorb spikes, stream events.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Synchronous service-to-service calls couple fate: if the consumer is slow or down, the producer blocks or fails. A message queue inserts a durable buffer between them — the producer drops a message and moves on, the consumer pulls when ready. This decouples teams, smooths traffic spikes into a backlog, and lets work survive crashes.","It's the backbone of async processing (emails, video transcode), event-driven architecture, and data pipelines."] },
    { h: "Queue vs log", p: ["Two families. A queue (RabbitMQ, SQS) pushes a message to one consumer and deletes it on ack — great for task distribution. A log (Kafka) is an append-only sequence consumers read by offset and which is retained for days, so many independent consumers can read it and replay history. Choose queue for tasks, log for streaming/replay."] },
    { h: "Kafka internals", p: ["A topic is split into partitions; each partition is an ordered, replicated, append-only file. Producers append; one partition has one leader and N replicas. Consumers form groups that split partitions for parallelism, tracking an offset (their position). Retention keeps messages for a window so replay/late consumers work."], bullets: ["Order is per-partition; key decides partition.","Replication factor 3 = survive 2 failures.","Offsets commit progress; retention enables replay."], code: `for (var r : consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100)))\n  if (seen.add(r.key())) process(r.value());   // idempotent\nconsumer.commitSync();                          // advance after work` },
    { h: "Delivery semantics", p: ["At-most-once may drop on failure; at-least-once is the common default and means duplicates happen — so consumers must be idempotent (dedupe by key); exactly-once needs transactions and is costly. Ordering only holds within a partition, so route related events to the same key."] },
    { h: "Reliability", bullets: ["Dead-letter queue after N failed attempts + alarm.","Backpressure: throttle producers on consumer lag.","Commit offset after processing (at-least-once).","Idempotent consumers are mandatory."] },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["Rebalance pauses on consumer join/leave.","Large messages bloat brokers (store blob, send pointer).","Commit-before-process drops data; ordering across keys not guaranteed."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Kafka vs SQS: replayable stream vs managed task queue.","Guarantee order: same key → same partition.","Exactly-once: idempotency + transactions.","Spike: queue absorbs it as backlog."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================================= RATE LIMITING ===== */
  { id: "dd-rl", cat: "Reliability", icon: "🚦", level: "Intermediate", title: "Rate Limiting", tagline: "Protect systems and enforce fair use.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["A single client or attacker can hammer an endpoint and exhaust shared capacity, starving everyone else. Rate limiting caps how many requests a key (user, IP, API key) may make per window, protecting backends, enforcing fairness/quotas, and blocking brute-force and scraping."] },
    { h: "Algorithms", p: ["Fixed window: count per minute, simple but allows 2x bursts at the boundary. Sliding window: smooths that with a moving range. Token bucket: tokens refill at a steady rate, each request spends one, empty→reject — allows controlled bursts, the common default. Leaky bucket: drains at a constant rate, smoothing output."], code: `t = min(cap, t + dt*rate);  // refill\nif (t >= 1) { t--; allow; } else reject(429);` },
    { h: "Distributed", p: ["With many app nodes the counter must be shared. A central Redis with an atomic Lua script does refill+consume in one round trip so two nodes can't both grab the last token. At extreme scale, give each node a local allowance and sync periodically — fast but slightly approximate."] },
    { h: "Failure policy", p: ["If the limiter store is down you must choose: fail-open (allow traffic, protect UX) or fail-closed (reject, protect backend). Public APIs usually fail-open with a local fallback; sensitive endpoints fail-closed."] },
    { h: "Response", bullets: ["Return 429 + Retry-After; expose X-RateLimit headers; tiered quotas per plan."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["1M rps: local buckets + periodic sync.","Allow bursts: token bucket.","Where: gateway, per user/key.","Store down: fail-open vs closed."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================================= INDEXING ========= */
  { id: "dd-index", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🗂️", level: "Intermediate → Advanced", title: "Indexing (B-tree vs LSM)", tagline: "Why a query is instant or scans a million rows.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Finding rows by a column with no index means scanning every row — O(n), seconds on millions of rows. An index is a separate sorted structure that turns that into O(log n), and enables range scans and ORDER BY for free. Choosing indexes well is the difference between 1ms and 10s."] },
    { h: "B-tree (read-optimized)", p: ["A balanced tree kept sorted by key; ~3–4 levels deep covers millions of rows, so a lookup is a handful of page reads. Leaf nodes link sideways for range scans. Updates modify pages in place. It's the default in Postgres/MySQL/Oracle — great for reads and ranges, moderate for writes."] },
    { h: "LSM-tree (write-optimized)", p: ["Writes go to an in-memory memtable, then flush to immutable sorted files (SSTables); background compaction merges them. Writes are sequential and fast; reads may check several files, so a Bloom filter per file skips ones that can't have the key. Powers Cassandra, RocksDB, LevelDB — ideal for write-heavy workloads."] },
    { h: "Rules of thumb", bullets: ["Index columns in WHERE / JOIN / ORDER BY.","Composite index obeys leftmost-prefix: (a,b) helps a and a+b, not b alone.","Each index speeds reads but slows writes and costs storage.","Covering index = query answered from the index, no row fetch."], code: `CREATE INDEX idx ON orders(user_id, created_at DESC); -- filter+sort` },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["Over-indexing kills write throughput.","Low-cardinality index (gender) barely helps.","LSM read/space amplification + compaction cost.","Function/leading-wildcard kills index use."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["B-tree vs LSM: read/range vs write-heavy.","Composite order matters (leftmost prefix).","Why slow query? missing/unusable index."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-bloom", cat: "Patterns", icon: "🌸", level: "Intermediate", title: "Bloom Filter", tagline: "Maybe present, definitely absent — in tiny space.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Asking 'have I seen this before?' against a huge set normally means a disk or DB lookup. A Bloom filter answers in a few in-memory bit checks: either 'definitely not present' (skip the expensive lookup entirely) or 'maybe present' (then verify). It uses a fraction of the memory a real set would, never gives a false negative, and only rarely a false positive."] },
    { h: "How it works", p: ["A bit array of m bits plus k hash functions. To insert, hash the item k ways and set those k bits. To query, hash and check all k bits: if any is 0 the item is definitely absent; if all are 1 it's probably present. More items eventually flip all bits, raising false positives, so size m and k for your n and target rate. Basic filters can't delete; a counting Bloom filter (counters not bits) can."], code: `void add(String s){ for(int i=0;i<k;i++) bit[idx(s,i)]=true; }\nboolean maybe(String s){ for(int i=0;i<k;i++) if(!bit[idx(s,i)]) return false; return true; }` },
    { h: "Uses", bullets: ["Cassandra/HBase skip SSTables that can't hold a key.","Cache-penetration guard (block lookups for keys that don't exist).","Dedup, spam/malicious-URL screening, CDN."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["False positives only; must size up front; can't enumerate; counting BF for deletes."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["FP vs FN: only FP.","Stop missing-key DB hits: front with Bloom.","Tune m,k for FP rate."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-lock", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "🔒", level: "Intermediate", title: "Distributed Locks", tagline: "One process at a time across many machines.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Two workers doing the same critical action (reserve the last item, run a singleton cron) corrupt state. A distributed lock gives mutual exclusion across processes that share no memory."] },
    { h: "How (Redis)", p: ["SET key token NX PX ttl: NX = only if absent, PX = expiry so a crashed holder auto-releases. Release only if you still own it via an atomic check-and-del; renew (heartbeat) for long work."], code: `set lock tok NX PX 30000; if(get(lock)==tok) del(lock); // safe release` },
    { h: "ZooKeeper/etcd", p: ["Ephemeral sequential nodes / leases tied to a session: lock auto-frees on disconnect; clients watch the predecessor to queue fairly."] },
    { h: "Fencing tokens", p: ["A lease can expire mid-work → two holders. Issue a monotonically increasing token; the resource rejects writes with stale tokens, preventing corruption."] },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["Clock skew + expiry; store SPOF; deadlocks; prefer idempotency over locks where possible."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Why TTL? avoid deadlock.","Redlock concerns? clock assumptions; fence.","Avoid lock? make op idempotent."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-consensus", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "🤝", level: "Advanced", title: "Consensus (Raft & Paxos)", tagline: "Many nodes agree on one truth despite crashes and delays.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Replicated systems must agree on order and leadership even when nodes crash or messages drop. Consensus produces a single consistent replicated log every node applies in the same order — the backbone of strongly-consistent stores.","It's how a cluster behaves like one reliable machine despite being many unreliable ones."] },
    { h: "Origin", p: ["Paxos (Lamport, 1998) proved agreement is possible but was notoriously hard. Raft (2014) made it understandable; it powers etcd, Consul, and the Kubernetes control plane."] },
    { h: "Raft step by step", p: ["Raft splits time into terms and gives nodes three roles. Followers wait for heartbeats; if none arrive a follower becomes a candidate, increments the term and requests votes; a majority makes it leader. The leader appends client commands to its log and replicates to followers; once a majority has stored an entry it is committed and applied to the state machine. A heartbeat keeps the leader; its loss triggers a new election."], bullets: ["Roles: leader / follower / candidate; numbered terms.","Election: timeout → candidate → majority vote.","Replicate → majority ack → commit → apply."], code: `int acks=1; for(Node f:followers) if(f.append(e)) acks++;\nboolean committed = acks > (followers.size()+1)/2;` },
    { h: "Why a majority quorum", p: ["Any two majorities of N share at least one node, so a committed entry is never lost across leader changes. That's why clusters are odd-sized: 3 tolerates 1 failure, 5 tolerates 2. A minority (e.g. partitioned 2 of 5) can't reach majority, so it can't commit — which is exactly how split-brain is prevented."] },
    { h: "Failure & safety", bullets: ["Leader crash → heartbeat timeout → re-election.","Split vote → randomized timeouts retry.","Partition → minority blocks, majority continues.","Log matching + commit index keep replicas identical."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["Write latency = quorum round-trip; throughput bounded by the single leader; needs majority alive. Use it to coordinate metadata/leadership, not to store bulk data."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Cluster size? odd (3/5).","Paxos vs Raft? same guarantees, Raft simpler.","Split-brain? minority can't reach quorum."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-cdn", cat: "Networking & Delivery", icon: "🌍", level: "Beginner", title: "CDN", tagline: "Serve content from the edge, near the user.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Distant users suffer high latency and the origin gets crushed by global read traffic. A CDN caches content at edge POPs worldwide so users hit a nearby server and the origin sees a fraction of requests."] },
    { h: "Origin", p: ["Akamai (1998, MIT) pioneered CDNs to cure the 'World Wide Wait'; Cloudflare/Fastly added programmable edges."] },
    { h: "How it works", p: ["DNS/Anycast routes the user to the nearest POP. Hit → serve cache; miss → fetch origin, cache per TTL, serve. Cache key, TTL, and purge control freshness."] },
    { h: "Freshness", bullets: ["Versioned URLs (app.v8.js) bust deterministically.","Purge API for emergencies; stale-while-revalidate."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["Personalized/dynamic content hard; invalidation lag; egress cost."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Cache bust? versioned URLs.","Dynamic? edge compute / no-store.","301 vs 302 for analytics."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-gw", cat: "Networking & Delivery", icon: "🚪", level: "Intermediate", title: "API Gateway", tagline: "One smart front door for many services.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Microservices create dozens of endpoints; without a gateway every service re-implements auth, throttling, logging, and clients juggle many hosts. A gateway is one entry point that routes, secures, and shapes all traffic."] },
    { h: "Origin", p: ["As SOA/microservices spread (2010s), Kong, Apigee, and AWS API Gateway centralized cross-cutting concerns at the edge of the service mesh."] },
    { h: "What it does", p: ["The gateway is a programmable reverse proxy that owns cross-cutting concerns so services stay focused on business logic. A request flows through a filter chain: terminate TLS, authenticate, rate-limit, validate, route, transform, and emit telemetry. It can also aggregate several backend calls into one response for a specific client (Backend-for-Frontend)."], bullets: ["TLS termination; AuthN/Z (JWT/API key)","Rate limiting + quotas; request validation","Routing by path/host; transform; retries","Metrics, logs, traces; BFF aggregation"], code: `if(!auth.valid(r.token())) return 401;\nif(!limit.allow(r.user())) return 429;\nreturn route(transform(r));` },
    { h: "Gateway vs LB vs mesh", p: ["Easy to confuse: a load balancer just distributes traffic; a gateway is the north-south policy front door for client→system; a service mesh handles east-west service→service concerns (mTLS, retries, telemetry) via sidecars. Big systems use all three."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["Can bottleneck if stuffed with logic; extra hop/latency; another thing to scale and secure. Keep it thin — policy and routing, never business logic."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Gateway vs mesh? front-door vs internal.","Avoid bottleneck? scale horizontally, no heavy logic.","BFF? per-client gateway."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-idem", cat: "Reliability", icon: "♻️", level: "Intermediate", title: "Idempotency", tagline: "Safe retries that never double-charge.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Networks time out and clients/queues retry. Without protection a retried 'charge' or 'create order' runs twice. Idempotency makes repeating an operation equal doing it once — the #1 property for payments."] },
    { h: "How", p: ["Client sends a unique idempotency key. Server stores key→result on first run; a duplicate key returns the stored result. Messaging dedupes by event id."], code: `Result r=store.get(key); if(r!=null)return r; r=charge(); store.putIfAbsent(key,r,24h); return r;` },
    { h: "Concurrency", bullets: ["Atomic putIfAbsent / unique key so two concurrent same-key requests don't both run.","TTL to clean up; durable store survives restarts."] },
    { h: "HTTP", bullets: ["GET/PUT/DELETE idempotent; POST not — add a key."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["At-least-once + dedupe ≈ exactly-once.","Key must be unique per logical op."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-saga", cat: "Patterns", icon: "🧵", level: "Advanced", title: "Saga & 2PC", tagline: "Multi-service transactions with compensations.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["A single ACID transaction can't span multiple services and databases — there's no shared lock. A saga models the workflow as a sequence of local transactions, each with a compensating action that semantically undoes it. If step 4 fails, you run the compensations for 3,2,1 to unwind. It trades atomicity for availability."] },
    { h: "2PC (and why it's rare)", p: ["Two-phase commit has a coordinator ask all participants to prepare, then commit. It gives true atomicity, but it blocks: if the coordinator dies after prepare, participants hold locks indefinitely, destroying availability. Across services it's mostly avoided in favor of sagas."] },
    { h: "Orchestration vs choreography", bullets: ["Orchestration: a central coordinator calls each step and its compensation — clear, easy to trace, but a hub.","Choreography: services emit/consume events with no coordinator — decoupled but hard to follow and debug."] },
    { h: "Example", p: ["Create order → charge payment → reserve stock. If reserve fails: refund the charge, cancel the order. Each step is idempotent (retries safe), each compensation explicit, and intermediate states are visible (no isolation) so design for that."], code: `charge(); try { reserve(); } catch { refund(); cancel(); }` },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["No isolation; visible partial states; complex failure trees; eventual consistency."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Saga vs 2PC? availability vs blocking atomicity.","Compensation must be idempotent."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-cb", cat: "Reliability", icon: "🔌", level: "Intermediate", title: "Resilience: Timeout, Retry, Circuit Breaker", tagline: "Keep one failure from cascading into an outage.", chapters: [
    { h: "Timeouts", p: ["A call with no deadline can hang forever and exhaust threads. Every remote call needs a timeout so it fails fast and frees resources. No timeout is a bug."] },
    { h: "Retries + backoff", bullets: ["Retry only idempotent ops, capped.","Exponential backoff (100/200/400ms) + jitter so clients don't retry in lockstep.","Bad retries amplify outages (retry storm)."] },
    { h: "Circuit breaker", p: ["Closed (normal) → Open after failure threshold (fail fast, don't call dead dep) → Half-open (probe) → Closed on success. Stops cascading failure."], code: `Open->after cooldown->HalfOpen->probe ok->Closed; probe fail->Open` },
    { h: "Bulkhead", p: ["Separate thread/connection pools per dependency so one slow dependency can't drain all capacity — like ship compartments."] },
    { h: "Graceful degradation", p: ["Serve cached/fallback when optional deps fail (popular feed if recs down) so the core stays alive."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Retry safe? only idempotent.","Jitter? desync clients.","Breaker states? closed/open/half."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-sqlnosql", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🗄️", level: "Beginner", title: "SQL vs NoSQL", tagline: "Pick storage by access pattern, not hype.", chapters: [
    { h: "SQL (relational)", p: ["Relational databases store rows in tables with a fixed schema and relate them by foreign keys, so you can join, run ad-hoc queries, and wrap multi-row changes in ACID transactions that are all-or-nothing. They are correct, flexible, and the right default for payments, orders, and anything relational. Scale reads with replicas; scaling writes/size means sharding, which is harder."] },
    { h: "NoSQL families", p: ["NoSQL is an umbrella for stores that drop joins/strict schema to scale horizontally:"], bullets: ["Key-value (Redis/Dynamo): blazing lookups by key.","Document (Mongo): flexible nested JSON.","Wide-column (Cassandra): write-heavy, time-series, multi-region.","Graph (Neo4j): relationships are the query."] },
    { h: "Why NoSQL exists", p: ["Web-scale write volume and evolving schemas outgrew single-node relational DBs. NoSQL trades joins and strong ACID for horizontal scale, flexible schema, and predictable by-key latency. You design tables around access patterns up front instead of querying freely later."] },
    { h: "How to choose", bullets: ["Default to SQL — flexible, correct, well understood.","Go NoSQL when access is by-key at huge scale, schema varies, or writes exceed one node.","Polyglot is normal: SQL for orders, KV for sessions, search for text, warehouse for analytics."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Need transactions/joins? SQL.","Billions of writes by key? wide-column.","Mixing both is expected."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-search", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🔎", level: "Intermediate", title: "Search & Inverted Index", tagline: "Find documents by content, ranked by relevance.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["SQL LIKE '%x%' scans every row and can't rank. Users want fast, typo-tolerant, relevance-ranked search. An inverted index makes term→document lookup instant."] },
    { h: "How it works", p: ["Documents are tokenized, normalized (lowercase, stem), and stored as term→postings (doc ids + positions). A query intersects postings; BM25/TF-IDF scores relevance. Built async from the DB — search is eventually consistent."], code: `index.computeIfAbsent(word,k->new HashSet<>()).add(docId);` },
    { h: "Features", bullets: ["Analyzers (stemming/synonyms), fuzzy match, facets, autocomplete, ranking."] },
    { h: "Keep in sync", bullets: ["DB is source of truth; index via events/CDC; reindex on mapping change."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Why not SQL? scan+rank.","Consistency? eventual.","Sync? CDC/events."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-auth", cat: "Security", icon: "🛡️", level: "Intermediate", title: "Auth: Sessions, JWT, OAuth2/OIDC", tagline: "Who you are, and what you may do.", chapters: [
    { h: "AuthN vs AuthZ", p: ["Authentication = prove identity. Authorization = decide permissions. Never conflate them."], bullets: ["AuthZ models: RBAC (roles), ABAC (attributes), ACL (per-object).","Default-deny: allow only what's explicit."] },
    { h: "Sessions vs JWT", bullets: ["Server session: id cookie → server store; revocable, central lookup.","JWT: signed token with claims; stateless, verified locally; revocation needs short TTL + denylist."], code: `JWT = base64(header).base64(payload).sign(secret); verify locally with public key` },
    { h: "OAuth2 flows", bullets: ["Authorization Code (+PKCE): web/mobile login.","Client credentials: service-to-service.","Access token (short) + refresh token (long)."] },
    { h: "OIDC", p: ["OpenID Connect adds an id_token (identity) on top of OAuth2's access tokens — the basis of 'Login with Google'."] },
    { h: "Service-to-service", bullets: ["mTLS for mutual identity; SPIFFE for workload identity; secrets in Vault, never in code."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["JWT revoke? short TTL + denylist.","Stateless scale? JWT.","Delegated access? OAuth2."] },
  ]},
  /* ============================ NEW BEGINNER-CRITICAL TOPICS ====== */
  { id: "dd-numbers", cat: "Fundamentals", icon: "🔢", level: "Beginner", title: "Latency Numbers & Estimation", tagline: "The numbers every engineer should know cold.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Designs live or die on rough math. Knowing relative speeds tells you where to put caches/CDNs and lets you size a system on a whiteboard in 60 seconds."] },
    { h: "Latency ladder", bullets: ["L1 ~1ns, L2 ~4ns, RAM ~100ns.","SSD read ~100µs, disk seek ~10ms.","Same-DC RTT ~0.5ms; cross-region ~50–150ms.","1 Gbps ≈ 125 MB/s."] },
    { h: "Powers of two", bullets: ["KB 10^3, MB 10^6, GB 10^9, TB 10^12. char=1B, int=4B, UUID=16B."] },
    { h: "Estimation recipe", bullets: ["QPS = DAU × actions/day ÷ 86400; peak × 2–5.","Storage = writes/day × size × retention.","Bandwidth = QPS × payload.","Servers = peak QPS ÷ per-box QPS."] },
    { h: "Example", p: ["100M DAU × 10 reads = 1B/day ≈ 11.6K QPS avg, ~35K peak. Cache 2KB items → ~70 MB/s. One Redis + a few app boxes handle it."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-dns", cat: "Networking & Delivery", icon: "🌐", level: "Beginner", title: "DNS", tagline: "Turning names into addresses, and routing users.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Humans use names, networks use IPs. DNS maps a domain to an address — and is the first place you can route users by geography, balance load, and fail over between regions."] },
    { h: "Resolution path", p: ["Client → recursive resolver → root → TLD (.com) → authoritative name server → returns the record. Every hop caches the answer for its TTL, so most lookups are instant."] },
    { h: "Records", bullets: ["A/AAAA: IPv4/IPv6.","CNAME: alias.","MX: mail.","TXT: SPF/verification.","NS: delegation."] },
    { h: "Routing tricks", bullets: ["Geo/latency routing, weighted, failover, Anycast (same IP, nearest POP)."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["TTL: low = fast failover but more queries; high = fewer queries, slow changes. Propagation isn't instant."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-http", cat: "Fundamentals", icon: "🔌", level: "Beginner", title: "HTTP, REST & gRPC", tagline: "How clients and services actually talk.", chapters: [
    { h: "HTTP basics", p: ["HTTP is a request/response text protocol over TCP. A request has a method, path, headers, and optional body; a response has a status code, headers, and body. It's stateless — each request stands alone, so servers scale by treating any request independently."], bullets: ["GET read, POST create, PUT replace, PATCH update, DELETE remove.","2xx ok, 3xx redirect, 4xx client error, 5xx server error.","GET/PUT/DELETE idempotent; POST is not."] },
    { h: "Versions", p: ["HTTP/1.1 added keep-alive (reuse a connection) but suffers head-of-line blocking. HTTP/2 multiplexes many streams over one connection. HTTP/3 runs over QUIC/UDP, removing TCP head-of-line and speeding up handshakes."] },
    { h: "REST", p: ["REST models everything as resources (/users/42) acted on by verbs, is stateless and cacheable, and is simple + universal. Downsides: over-fetch (too much data) and under-fetch (many round trips) for complex screens."] },
    { h: "gRPC", p: ["Binary protobuf over HTTP/2: compact, typed, supports streaming — ideal for fast internal service-to-service RPC. Not browser-native, less human-readable."] },
    { h: "GraphQL", p: ["One endpoint where the client specifies exactly which fields it wants, killing over/under-fetch. Cost: caching and query-complexity control are harder."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["REST vs gRPC: public/simple vs internal/fast.","Idempotent methods: GET/PUT/DELETE.","Why HTTP/2: multiplexing."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-micro", cat: "Scaling", icon: "🧱", level: "Intermediate", title: "Monolith vs Microservices", tagline: "Split by team and bounded context.", chapters: [
    { h: "Monolith", p: ["One codebase, one deploy, one DB. Calls are in-process (fast), transactions are trivial, and debugging is local. It's the right start for almost everyone. The pain comes later: a big team steps on each other, one bug can take down everything, and you must scale the whole app even if only one part is hot."] },
    { h: "Microservices", p: ["Independent services, each deployable on its own, owning its database, scaled and released by its own team. The price is distributed-systems complexity: network calls fail, data is eventually consistent, and you need tracing, service discovery, and a lot more ops."] },
    { h: "Boundaries", p: ["Split by bounded context (DDD), not by technical layer. A good service owns one capability and its data; database-per-service is what makes services truly independent — a shared DB recouples them into a distributed monolith."] },
    { h: "Decision", p: ["Monolith-first. Extract a service only when a boundary genuinely hurts: it scales differently, a team needs autonomy, or deploy cadence conflicts. Don't start with 20 services."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["When microservices? large teams + independent scale.","Cross-service txn? saga.","Shared DB = anti-pattern."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-scale", cat: "Scaling", icon: "📈", level: "Beginner", title: "Scaling & Statelessness", tagline: "Up vs out, and why stateless wins.", chapters: [
    { h: "Vertical vs horizontal", bullets: ["Up: bigger box — simple, capped, pricey at top, SPOF.","Out: more boxes — scales far, needs distribution + LB."] },
    { h: "Stateless services", p: ["Keep no local state; put it in cache/DB/session store. Any instance serves any request → trivial autoscale, rolling deploys, and failover."] },
    { h: "Autoscaling", bullets: ["Scale on CPU/QPS/queue depth; min/max bounds; pre-warm for spikes faster than scale-up."] },
    { h: "Backpressure", p: ["When consumers can't keep up, push back: 429s, bounded queues, blocking — controlled slowdown beats a crash."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Stateless why? scale/failover.","Sticky sessions cost.","Spike handling: pre-warm + queue."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-obs", cat: "Reliability", icon: "📊", level: "Intermediate", title: "Observability", tagline: "Logs, metrics, traces — and SLOs.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["You can't run what you can't see. When something breaks you must know what happened, how bad, and where. Observability is metrics + logs + traces working together."] },
    { h: "Three pillars", bullets: ["Logs: discrete events (what happened).","Metrics: numbers over time — QPS, p99 latency, errors, CPU, queue depth.","Traces: one request across services with timing per span."] },
    { h: "SLI / SLO / SLA", bullets: ["SLI: measured indicator. SLO: target (p99<300ms). SLA: contract. Error budget drives release pace."] },
    { h: "Alerting", bullets: ["Alert on symptoms (SLO at risk), not noise; pages → on-call; runbooks for response."] },
    { h: "Tools", bullets: ["Prometheus/Grafana, ELK/OpenSearch, OpenTelemetry+Jaeger, Datadog, PagerDuty."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Where slow? traces.","Alert on what? SLO breach.","3 pillars name them."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-ws", cat: "Networking & Delivery", icon: "🔁", level: "Intermediate", title: "WebSockets & Realtime", tagline: "Pushing updates without polling.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Polling wastes requests and adds latency. WebSockets keep a single persistent, bidirectional TCP connection so the server pushes updates instantly — chat, live dashboards, notifications."] },
    { h: "How", p: ["Start as HTTP, send Upgrade → 101 Switching Protocols → full-duplex WS. Stateful gateways hold thousands of sockets; a session registry maps user→gateway so any node can reach any client."] },
    { h: "Fan-out", p: ["Back gateways with pub/sub (Redis/Kafka) so a message published once reaches whoever holds the recipient's socket. Large groups: write once, subscribers read."] },
    { h: "Alternatives", bullets: ["SSE (server→client only), long-poll fallback, HTTP/2 push."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["Stateful = harder scale/deploy; connection limits; reconnection/heartbeats."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-obj", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🪣", level: "Beginner", title: "Object Storage", tagline: "Cheap durable blobs at any scale.", chapters: [
    { h: "What & why", p: ["Images, video, backups, and ML datasets don't belong in a transactional database — they bloat it and are read in bulk. Object storage (S3/GCS/Azure Blob) holds them as immutable objects in flat buckets, cheap, durable to 11 nines, and effectively infinite, served fast through a CDN."] },
    { h: "How it works", p: ["You PUT/GET by key; there's no folder tree, just a flat namespace. Durability comes from replicating or erasure-coding each object across machines/zones. Store the blob's URL + metadata in your database, not the bytes. Lifecycle rules tier old data hot→cold (Glacier) to cut cost."] },
    { h: "Tradeoffs", bullets: ["No partial/row updates (replace whole object); listing is eventual; egress is the cost trap; not for low-latency transactions."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Where store images? object store + CDN, URL in DB.","Durability? replication/erasure coding.","Big-file upload? multipart + presigned URLs."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-tsdb", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "⏱️", level: "Intermediate", title: "Time-Series & Graph DBs", tagline: "Specialized stores for metrics and relationships.", chapters: [
    { h: "Time-series", p: ["Metrics and IoT data are append-heavy and queried by time range. A TSDB stores points indexed by timestamp, compresses aggressively, downsamples old data (1s→1m→1h), and expires it via retention. InfluxDB, TimescaleDB, Prometheus. Use: monitoring, IoT sensors, finance ticks."] },
    { h: "Graph", p: ["When relationships ARE the query (friends-of-friends, fraud rings), recursive SQL joins explode. Graph DBs store nodes + edges so a traversal is O(neighbors), not O(table). Neo4j, Neptune. Use: social graph, recommendations, fraud."] },
    { h: "When to use", p: ["Both are niche — reach for them only when the access pattern truly demands it; otherwise SQL/NoSQL is simpler. Time-series for dense temporal data, graph for deep relationship traversals."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-warehouse", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🏭", level: "Intermediate", title: "Warehouse, Lake & OLAP", tagline: "Analytics over huge historical data.", chapters: [
    { h: "OLTP vs OLAP", bullets: ["OLTP: many small row reads/writes serving the app (Postgres).","OLAP: few huge columnar scans answering business questions (Snowflake)."] },
    { h: "Warehouse vs lake", bullets: ["Warehouse: structured columnar SQL analytics (BigQuery/Redshift).","Lake: raw cheap object storage, schema-on-read (S3).","Lakehouse unifies both (Databricks/Delta)."] },
    { h: "Pipeline", p: ["OLTP + logs → ETL/ELT → warehouse → BI. Never run heavy analytics on the OLTP DB — it crushes the app."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-deploy", cat: "Reliability", icon: "🚀", level: "Intermediate", title: "Safe Deploys: Canary, Blue-Green, Flags", tagline: "Ship without taking the site down.", chapters: [
    { h: "Canary", p: ["Route a small % (e.g. 5%) to the new version, watch error/latency, ramp up if healthy, roll back instantly if not."] },
    { h: "Blue-green", p: ["Run two identical environments; deploy to green, validate, switch the LB; rollback = switch back. Zero-downtime."] },
    { h: "Feature flags", p: ["Decouple deploy from release: ship code dark, flip a flag to enable for cohorts; instant kill switch."] },
    { h: "Rolling", p: ["Replace instances batch-by-batch behind the LB; readiness gates keep traffic on healthy nodes."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-tls", cat: "Security", icon: "🔐", level: "Intermediate", title: "TLS & Encryption", tagline: "Protect data in transit and at rest.", chapters: [
    { h: "In transit", p: ["TLS encrypts data on the wire so it can't be read or tampered with. The handshake authenticates the server via its certificate, agrees a cipher, and derives a session key. mTLS adds a client certificate so both sides prove identity — the standard for service-to-service inside a mesh."] },
    { h: "At rest", p: ["Encrypt disks, DB files, and buckets with keys managed by a KMS so a stolen snapshot is useless. Often combined with envelope encryption: a master key encrypts per-object data keys."] },
    { h: "Secrets", bullets: ["Vault/KMS/Secrets Manager store credentials; fetch at runtime, rotate regularly, never hardcode."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["In-transit vs at-rest cover network vs storage.","mTLS = mutual identity.","Rotate keys; never commit secrets."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-leader", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "👑", level: "Advanced", title: "Leader Election", tagline: "Pick one coordinator; replace it on failure.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["Some jobs must have exactly one owner: the primary that accepts writes, a cron that runs once, the owner of a shard. Leader election picks one node and automatically re-picks if it dies, so the system has a single coordinator without manual intervention."] },
    { h: "How", p: ["Use a coordination service: ZooKeeper ephemeral node, etcd lease, or a Raft cluster's own leader. Candidates race to create the lock/lease; the winner sends heartbeats; if they stop, others elect a new leader. Quorum ensures only one winner."] },
    { h: "Fencing", p: ["A slow leader whose lease expired might still issue writes. Hand each leader a monotonically increasing epoch/fencing token; resources reject anything with an old token, so a zombie leader can't corrupt state."] },
    { h: "Pitfalls", bullets: ["Split-brain without quorum; zombie leader → fence; election storms → randomized timeouts."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-geo", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "📍", level: "Intermediate", title: "Geospatial Indexing", tagline: "Find nearby points fast.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why", p: ["'Drivers within 2km' on a plain lat/long table means scanning every row and computing distance — hopeless at scale. Encode each location into a grid cell so 'nearby' becomes 'same or adjacent cell', turning search into a few key lookups."] },
    { h: "Techniques", p: ["Geohash encodes lat/long into a short string where shared prefixes mean proximity. S2 maps the globe onto a Hilbert curve of cells. QuadTree subdivides space adaptively. Store points in Redis keyed by cell; query the rider's cell plus neighbors."] },
    { h: "Use", p: ["Uber driver matching, maps, store locators, geofencing. Tune cell size to density — small cells for cities, large for rural — to balance precision vs lookups."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-modeling", cat: "Data & Storage", icon: "🧩", level: "Intermediate", title: "Data Modeling & Denormalization", tagline: "Shape data for the queries you'll run.", chapters: [
    { h: "Normalize vs denormalize", p: ["Normalization removes duplication: each fact lives once, writes are clean, but reads need joins. Denormalization copies data so a read needs no joins — fast reads, but writes must update every copy and consistency gets harder. SQL leans normalized; NoSQL leans denormalized."] },
    { h: "Model the query (NoSQL)", p: ["In NoSQL there are no joins to lean on, so you design tables around access patterns up front. The partition key and sort key decide everything: what you can fetch in one call and in what order. Get the keys wrong and the workload is impossible — plan queries before schema."] },
    { h: "Materialized views", p: ["Precompute expensive aggregations or feeds and store the result; refresh on a cadence or via events. Reads become instant at the cost of staleness and refresh complexity — the same denormalization tradeoff applied to derived data."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Read-heavy screen: denormalize.","NoSQL design: per access pattern.","Aggregations: materialized view."] },
  ]},
  { id: "dd-ordering", cat: "Distributed Systems", icon: "🔢", level: "Advanced", title: "Ordering & Exactly-Once", tagline: "Make distributed events land in the right order, once.", chapters: [
    { h: "Why it's hard", p: ["Across machines, clocks drift (skew), so wall-clock timestamps can't reliably order events. Networks reorder and retry, so the same event may arrive twice or out of sequence. You need logical ordering plus deduplication, not the system clock."] },
    { h: "Logical clocks", p: ["Lamport timestamps give a consistent total-ish order; vector clocks capture causality (who-knew-what); Kafka gives a strict order within a partition via offsets. Pick the weakest that solves your problem — full global order is expensive."] },
    { h: "Exactly-once", p: ["True exactly-once delivery is nearly impossible; the practical recipe is at-least-once delivery + an idempotent consumer (dedupe by event id). Route related events to the same partition key so order is preserved where it matters."] },
    { h: "Interview Q&A", bullets: ["Order across machines? logical clocks, not wall time.","Exactly-once? at-least-once + dedupe.","Keep order? same key → same partition."] },
  ]},
];
